<p><em><a href="/podcasts/">Subscribe to all the FiveThirtyEight podcasts</a>.</em></p><div class="ornamental-rule"><hr><span></span></div>

<p>Scientists who fiddle around like this — just about all of them do, Simonsohn told me — aren’t usually committing fraud, nor are they intending to. They’re just falling prey to natural human biases that lead them to tip the scales and set up studies to produce false-positive results.</p>
<p>Since publishing novel results can garner a scientist rewards such as tenure and jobs, there’s ample incentive to p-hack. Indeed, when Simonsohn analyzed the distribution of p-values in published psychology papers, he found that they were suspiciously concentrated around 0.05. “Everybody has p-hacked at least a little bit,” Simonsohn told me.</p>
<p>But that doesn’t mean researchers are a bunch of hucksters, a la LaCour. What it means is that they’re human. P-hacking and similar types of manipulations often arise from human biases. “You can do it in unconscious ways —<i>I’ve</i> done it in unconscious ways,” Simonsohn said. “You really believe your hypothesis and you get the data and there’s ambiguity about how to analyze it.” When the first analysis you try doesn’t spit out the result you want, you keep trying until you find one that does. (And if that doesn’t work, you can always fall back on <a href="http://mres.gmu.edu/readings/Kerr1998.pdf">HARKing — hypothesizing after the results are known</a>.)</p>
<p>Subtle (or not-so-subtle) manipulations like these plague so many studies that Stanford meta-science researcher John Ioannidis concluded, in a famous 2005 paper, that <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1182327/">most published research findings are false</a>. “It’s really difficult to perform a good study,” he told me, admitting that he has surely published incorrect findings too. “There are so many potential biases and errors and issues that can interfere with getting a reliable, credible result.” Yet despite this conclusion, Ioannidis has not sworn off science. Instead, he’s sworn to protect it.</p>
<div class="ornamental-rule"><hr><span></span></div>

<figure id="attachment_86783" class="wp-caption alignnone full-width" style="max-width: 2048px">
					<img decoding="async" class="full-width size-full wp-image-86783" src="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg" alt="SCIENCE_SPOT_2048" width="1024" height="575" srcset="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg 2048w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=100,56 100w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=300,169 300w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=768,432 768w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=1024,576 1024w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=1536,863 1536w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=683,384 683w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=575,323 575w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=470,264 470w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=600,337 600w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=463,260 463w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=285,160 285w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=207,116 207w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=60,34 60w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" data-sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" data-src="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg" data-srcset="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg 2048w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=100,56 100w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=300,169 300w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=768,432 768w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=1024,576 1024w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=1536,863 1536w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=683,384 683w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=575,323 575w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=470,264 470w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=600,337 600w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=463,260 463w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=285,160 285w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=207,116 207w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/science_spot_2048.jpg?resize=60,34 60w"><figcaption class="wp-caption-text caption">
															<p class="photo-credit credits">Illustration by Shout</p></figcaption>
						</figure>
		
<section id="part2"><span class="drop-cap">P</span>-hacking is generally thought of as cheating, but what if we made it compulsory instead? If the purpose of studies is to push the frontiers of knowledge, then perhaps playing around with different methods shouldn’t be thought of as a dirty trick, but encouraged as a way of exploring boundaries. A recent project spearheaded by <a href="http://projectimplicit.net/nosek/">Brian Nosek</a>, a founder of the nonprofit <a href="http://centerforopenscience.org/">Center for Open Science</a>, offered a clever way to do this.
<p>Nosek’s team invited researchers to take part in a crowdsourcing data analysis project. The setup was simple. Participants were all given the same data set and prompt: Do soccer referees give more red cards to dark-skinned players than light-skinned ones? They were then asked to submit their analytical approach for <a href="https://osf.io/2prib/">feedback from other teams</a> before diving into the analysis.</p>
<p>Twenty-nine teams with a total of 61 analysts took part. The researchers used a wide variety of methods, ranging — for those of you interested in the methodological gore — from simple linear regression techniques to complex multilevel regressions and Bayesian approaches. They also made <a href="https://osf.io/sea6k/">different decisions</a> about which secondary variables to use in their analyses.</p>
<p>Despite analyzing the same data, <a href="https://osf.io/j5v8f/">the researchers got a variety of results</a>. Twenty teams concluded that soccer referees gave more red cards to dark-skinned players, and nine teams found no significant relationship between skin color and red cards.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" class="full-width hide-mobile alignnone wp-image-86937" src="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png" alt="truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls" width="1024" height="597" srcset="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png 2048w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=100,58 100w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=300,175 300w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=768,448 768w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=1024,597 1024w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=1536,896 1536w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=683,398 683w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=575,335 575w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=470,274 470w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=600,350 600w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=446,260 446w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=274,160 274w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=988,576 988w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=207,121 207w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=60,35 60w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" data-sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" data-src="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png" data-srcset="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png 2048w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=100,58 100w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=300,175 300w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=768,448 768w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=1024,597 1024w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=1536,896 1536w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=683,398 683w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=575,335 575w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=470,274 470w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=600,350 600w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=446,260 446w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=274,160 274w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=988,576 988w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=207,121 207w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls2.png?resize=60,35 60w"></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="show-mobile alignnone wp-image-86939" src="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png" alt="truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile" width="610" height="2410" srcset="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png 620w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=19,75 19w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=76,300 76w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=259,1024 259w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=389,1536 389w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=518,2048 518w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=109,432 109w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=89,352 89w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=57,225 57w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=114,450 114w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=66,260 66w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=146,576 146w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=39,155 39w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=25,100 25w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=15,60 15w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=174,687 174w" sizes="(max-width: 610px) 100vw, 610px" data-sizes="(max-width: 610px) 100vw, 610px" data-src="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png" data-srcset="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png 620w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=19,75 19w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=76,300 76w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=259,1024 259w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=389,1536 389w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=518,2048 518w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=109,432 109w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=89,352 89w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=57,225 57w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=114,450 114w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=66,260 66w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=146,576 146w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=39,155 39w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=25,100 25w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=15,60 15w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-soccer-calls-mobile.png?resize=174,687 174w"></p>
<p>The variability in results wasn’t due to fraud or sloppy work. These were highly competent analysts who were motivated to find the truth, said <a href="http://www.insead.edu/facultyresearch/faculty/profiles/euhlmann/">Eric Luis Uhlmann</a>, a psychologist at the Insead business school in Singapore and one of the project leaders. Even the most skilled researchers must make subjective choices that have a huge impact on the result they find.</p>
<p>But these disparate results don’t mean that studies can’t inch us toward truth. “On the one hand, our study shows that results are heavily reliant on analytic choices,” Uhlmann told me. “On the other hand, it also suggests there’s a <i>there</i> there. It’s hard to look at that data and say there’s no bias against dark-skinned players.” Similarly, most of the permutations you could test in the study of politics and the economy produced, at best, only weak effects, which suggests that if there’s a relationship between the number of Democrats or Republicans in office and the economy, it’s not a strong one.</p>
<p>The important lesson here is that a single analysis is not sufficient to find a definitive answer. Every result is a temporary truth, one that’s subject to change when someone else comes along to build, test and analyze anew.</p>
</section>
<section id="part3"><div class="ornamental-rule"><hr><span></span></div>

<p><span class="drop-cap">W</span>hat makes science so powerful is that it’s self-correcting — sure, false findings get published, but eventually new studies come along to overturn them, and the truth is revealed. At least, that’s how it’s supposed to work. But scientific publishing doesn’t have a great track record when it comes to self-correction. In 2010, Ivan Oransky, a physician and editorial director at <a href="http://www.medpagetoday.com/">MedPage Today</a>, launched a blog called <a href="http://retractionwatch.com/">Retraction Watch</a> with Adam Marcus, managing editor of Gastroenterology &amp; Endoscopy News and Anesthesiology News. The two had been professional acquaintances and became friendly while covering <a href="http://www.anesthesiologynews.com/ViewArticle.aspx?d=Policy+&amp;+Management&amp;d_id=3&amp;i=March+2009&amp;i_id=494&amp;a_id=12634&amp;ses=ogst">the case against Scott Reuben</a>, an anesthesiologist who in 2009 was caught faking data in at least 21 studies.</p>
<p>The first Retraction Watch post was titled “<a href="http://retractionwatch.com/2010/08/03/why-write-a-blog-about-retractions/">Why write a blog about retractions?</a>” Five years later, the answer seems self-evident: Because without a concerted effort to pay attention, nobody will notice what was wrong in the first place. “I thought we might do one post a month,” Marcus told me. “I don’t think either of us thought it would become two or three a day.” But after an interview on public radio and media attention highlighting the blog’s coverage of <a href="http://retractionwatch.com/2010/08/10/monkey-business-2002-cognition-paper-retracted-as-prominent-psychologist-marc-hauser-takes-leave-from-harvard/">Marc Hauser, a Harvard psychologist caught fabricating data</a>, the tips started rolling in. “What became clear is that there was a very large number of people in science who were frustrated with the way that misconduct was being handled, and these people found us very quickly,” Oransky said. The site now draws 125,000 unique views each month.</p>
<p>While the site still focuses on retractions and corrections, it also covers broader misconduct and errors. Most importantly, “it’s a platform where people can discuss and uncover instances of data fabrication,” said Daniele Fanelli, a senior research scientist at Stanford’s Meta-Research Innovation Center. Reader tips have helped create a surge in content, and the site now employs several staff members and is building a comprehensive, freely available database of retractions with help from a <a href="http://retractionwatch.com/2014/12/15/retraction-watch-growing-thanks-400000">$400,000 MacArthur Foundation grant</a>.</p>
<p>Marcus and Oransky contend that retractions shouldn’t automatically be viewed as a stain on the scientific enterprise; instead, they signal that science is fixing its mistakes.</p>
<p>Retractions happen for a variety of reasons, but plagiarism and image manipulations (rigging images from microscopes or gels, for instance, to show the desired results) are the two most common ones, Marcus told me. While outright fabrications are relatively rare, most errors aren’t just honest mistakes. A 2012 study by University of Washington microbiologist Ferric Fang and his colleagues concluded that <a href="http://www.pnas.org/content/109/42/17028">two-thirds of retractions were due to misconduct</a>.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="hide-mobile alignnone wp-image-86890" src="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png" alt="truth-vigilantes-retractions" width="610" height="475" srcset="https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png 1220w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=96,75 96w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=300,234 300w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=768,598 768w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=1024,797 1024w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=658,512 658w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=555,432 555w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=452,352 452w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=289,225 289w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=578,450 578w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=334,260 334w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=205,160 205w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=740,576 740w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=199,155 199w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=100,78 100w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/truth-vigilantes-retractions.png?resize=60,47 60w, https://fivethirtyeight.com/